          "body": "When the manna appears, Israel asks 'What is it?' (*man hu*, 16:15) — the question that becomes the substance's name. It is fine, flake-like, white as coriander seed, sweet as wafers with honey (16:14, 31). Moses explains the gathering rules: one omer per person (16:16), nothing left until morning (16:19). The test is built into the structure of the gift. God could have given Israel a warehouse. He gave them daily bread. The reason is stated from the beginning: 'that I may test them, whether or not they will walk in My instruction' (16:4). Daily gathering is the physical form of daily faith. Hoarding is the physical form of distrust. The miracle enforces the test: those who hoard find worms and stench (16:20); those who gather only what is needed find sufficiency. The equality of the provision is remarkable — 'he who had gathered much had no excess, and he who had gathered little had no lack' (16:18). Paul reads this verse through the lens of Christian generosity in 2 Corinthians 8:15, applying the manna-principle to the church's economic sharing: divine provision equalizes effort and produces sufficiency, not accumulation. The manna test is a school in the economics of grace."
