          "body": "The chapter closes not with the end of manna but with its preservation. Moses commands that an omer be kept 'throughout your generations, that they may see the bread that I fed you in the wilderness, when I brought you out of the land of Egypt' (16:32). Aaron places the jar of manna 'before the Testimony' (16:34) — before the ark of the covenant where the tablets of the law will be kept. The jar of manna, the tablets of the covenant, and (by Numbers 17:10) Aaron's budded rod together constitute the three memorial objects placed within or before the ark (cf. Hebrews 9:4). The manna-jar is not a relic of sentimentality; it is a permanent witness to the character of God. Future generations who never walked through the wilderness of Sin will see the actual substance of God's provision and know what He did. The note of verse 35 — forty years of manna until the border of Canaan — frames the entire chapter as the compressed beginning of a decades-long testimony. Every morning for forty years, the manna appeared. Every morning, Israel had the choice: trust and gather what is given, or distrust and hoard what will rot. The chapter is thus not a single event but the overture to a forty-year school in divine sufficiency."
